{"id":227,"date":"2006-03-30T16:41:43","date_gmt":"2006-03-31T00:41:43","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wordpress\/?p=227"},"modified":"2006-03-30T16:41:43","modified_gmt":"2006-03-31T00:41:43","slug":"why-i-wont-work-at-google","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/2006\/03\/why-i-wont-work-at-google\/","title":{"rendered":"Why I won&#8217;t work at Google"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>&lt;rant&gt;<br \/>\nPeter Norvig <a href=\"http:\/\/googleresearch.blogspot.com\/2006\/03\/hiring-lake-wobegon-strategy.html\">discusses<\/a> the &#8220;no hiring manager&#8221; philiosophy of Google, which I&#8217;ve heard related several times in conversation. &#8220;First we decide which candidates are above the hiring threshold, and then we decide what projects they can best contribute to.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>When I&#8217;m looking for a job, I&#8217;m interested:<br \/>\n1) working with a specific group of awesome people<br \/>\n2) developing and releasing a product that will make a difference<br \/>\n3) working on interesting, innovative tech<\/p>\n<p>There is no way I&#8217;m even touching a company that wants to hire me into a pool of candidates that will then be offered specific jobs. I&#8217;m sure Google is a great company to work for.  I know a lot of people there who are very happy, and not just about the stock options.  I just don&#8217;t work that way.<\/p>\n<p>And another thing: as a hiring manager, I&#8217;ve never hired someone sub-standard just to get a project done.  If I&#8217;m desperate, I can usually find a contractor who because of their preference or mine would never be a full-time hire.  Who wants a sub-standard dork on their *next* project?  I&#8217;m not saying it doesn&#8217;t happen.  I&#8217;m just saying hire good managers and create an interview process that makes it near impossible to hire the sub-standard.<br \/>\n&lt;\/rant&gt;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>&lt;rant&gt; Peter N